I reported this in Fedora 23 as well (https://bugzilla.redhat.com/show_bug.cgi?id=1360705). But reposting here:
1. I think it's a regression in kernel version 4.6, caused by the cpufreq changes.
Article on cpufreq changes: https://lwn.net/Articles/682391/
First kernel version reporting this in ABRT: 4.6.0-0.rc6.git0.1.fc25
2. This happens on resume from suspend. On my Thinkpad X201, I can reproduce it reliably if I plug in to mains power, close the lid to trigger suspend, unplug from mains power, and then wake the system up again.

Looks like upstream are aware, with some progress for a fix to be submitted to upstream stable trees.
https://lkml.org/lkml/2016/6/27/704

Hello, Following the tip, I found https://patchwork.kernel.org/patch/9199789/ shows State Accepted, archived and looks like that is in kernel-4.7.0 : https://git.kernel.org/cgit/linux/kernel/git/torvalds/linux.git/diff/drivers/cpufreq/cpufreq.c?id=v4.7&id2=v4.6
So I built kernel-4.7.0-2 on copr https://copr.fedorainfracloud.org/coprs/sergiomb/builds_for_Stable_Releases/ copied src.rpm for koji [1]
I testing ATM , after after 2 or 3 resumes , seems that is no more ooops.
[1] http://koji.fedoraproject.org/koji/packageinfo?packageID=8 http://koji.fedoraproject.org/koji/buildinfo?buildID=785559

(In reply to Sergio Monteiro Basto from comment #6) > Hello, > Following the tip, I found https://patchwork.kernel.org/patch/9199789/ > shows State Accepted, archived and looks like that is in kernel-4.7.0 : > https://git.kernel.org/cgit/linux/kernel/git/torvalds/linux.git/diff/drivers/ > cpufreq/cpufreq.c?id=v4.7&id2=v4.6 > > So I built kernel-4.7.0-2 on copr > https://copr.fedorainfracloud.org/coprs/sergiomb/builds_for_Stable_Releases/ > copied src.rpm for koji [1]
You don't need to do that. You can install 4.7.0-2 that is already built in koji. Also, while it is great that you took the initiative and we appreciate the testing, the more people do these micro-fork kernel builds in COPR, the more we have a proliferation of kernels from random places. That isn't sustainable in the long run.

(In reply to Josh Boyer from comment #7) > You can install 4.7.0-2 that is already built in > koji.
we don't have 4.7.0-2 for F23 neither for F24 !

(In reply to Sergio Monteiro Basto from comment #8) > (In reply to Josh Boyer from comment #7) > > You can install 4.7.0-2 that is already built in > > koji. > > we don't have 4.7.0-2 for F23 neither for F24 !
